$$ Strategy: launch, set a sxe callback on module-load that:
$$   - checks if the just-loaded module is Adobe AIR (by looking at the
$$     range around the address in @$curframe), then sets the real bp.
$$ We use a looser filter: break on *any* module load whose name contains
$$ "Adobe". In practice only one such DLL loads.

.logopen /t C:\Users\Joao\IdeaProjects\ane-awesome-utils\tests\rva-probe\probe.log

$$ Break on module load. We'll filter inside the callback script because
$$ sxe ld:<name> filters are string-matched against the unquoted module
$$ short-name, which dislikes the space in "Adobe AIR".
sxe -c "$$>< C:\\Users\\Joao\\IdeaProjects\\ane-awesome-utils\\tests\\rva-probe\\on_module_load.cdb" ld

$$ Counter for send_bytes hits.
r $t0 = 0x14

$$ Run until a qualifying module load hits.
g

.echo [probe] process exited before 20 send_bytes hits
.logclose
qq
